AG Charlotte Davidson 03/18/2023 11:50 PM
It has two primary purposes: a) it will shorten the timespan that the President has to report to Congress that they had sent troops to a place abroad (given that 60 days lasts longer than a single term in office, so it doesn't make sense to have such a long time) and b) it clarifies the War Powers Resolution of 1973.
AG Charlotte Davidson 03/18/2023 11:50 PM
The motion that I made isn't to vote on the bill btw, it's just to get it into a committee.
AG Charlotte Davidson 03/18/2023 11:54 PM
It's mainly cleaning up the language of the existing statute.
AG Charlotte Davidson 03/18/2023 11:57 PM
I should clarify that this doesn't shorten any deployments [at least within reason], it just shortens the time that the president must notify Congress of deployments and shortens the time that Congress must act on whether to keep troops or withdraw them.
AG Charlotte Davidson 03/18/2023 11:58 PM
I think it's a good bill that should've been passed a long, long time ago but hey it's happening now.

AG Charlotte Davidson 03/19/2023 09:06 PM
I think there’s some confusion, it’s not restricting the President’s authority to send troops abroad or on deployments. One of the two things that are changing is shortening the time scale from 60 days to 7 days for when the President has to notify Congress that he or she sent troops abroad. And then giving Congress up to a number of days when both chambers have to vote on whether to keep the funding for those troops on deployment or take it away.
AG Charlotte Davidson 03/19/2023 09:06 PM
It doesn’t.
AG Charlotte Davidson 03/19/2023 09:09 PM
I’m aware. This isn’t changing how long campaigns can go for nor is it changing what the previous number of days for Congress to consider it. Again nothing was changed with the 60 days to act, that wasn’t reduced.

The only thing my proposed joint resolution is changing is shortening the number of days before the President is obligated to report to Congress that he or she deployed troops to somewhere.
AG Charlotte Davidson 03/19/2023 09:13 PM
There is that chance though highly unlikely given… well this is Congress. I’ve never really seen anything speedily happen.

However, it is our constitutional mandate, right, and power to control the purse and to declare war- only Congress can do that. So if the President decides to send troops to where troops shouldn’t belong too, than Congress should be able to act promptly to stop such an incursion. The intentions of my joint resolution is rebalance the separation of powers in something that has long been tipped further and further to the executive branch- and I say that as a former President.
AG Charlotte Davidson 03/19/2023 09:14 PM
Yes, the President is Commander and Chief and has certain war powers and special powers that may come with that but it shouldn’t be for an idiotic incursion to another country on a whim or made up provocation. It should be because Congress either authorized deployments and/or declared war.
Marksman 03/19/2023 09:26 PM
It would restrict the Presidents authority to send troops abroad because the requirement to withdraw troops after 60 days falls under 50 U.S. Code § 1544 which states

Within sixty calendar days after a report is submitted or is required to be submitted pursuant to section 1543(a)(1) of this title, whichever is earlier, the President shall terminate any use of United States Armed Forces with respect to which such report was submitted (or required to be submitted), unless the Congress (1) has declared war or has enacted a specific authorization for such use of United States Armed Forces, (2) has extended by law such sixty-day period, or (3) is physically unable to meet as a result of an armed attack upon the United States. Such sixty-day period shall be extended for not more than an additional thirty days if the President determines and certifies to the Congress in writing that unavoidable military necessity respecting the safety of United States Armed Forces requires the continued use of such armed forces in the course of bringing about a prompt removal of such forces.

And section 1543(a)(1) includes

``(1)into hostilities or into situations where imminent involvement in hostilities is clearly indicated by the circumstances;
(2)into the territory, airspace or waters of a foreign nation, while equipped for combat, except for deployments which relate solely to supply, replacement, repair, or training of such forces; or
(3)in numbers which substantially enlarge United States Armed Forces equipped for combat already located in a foreign nation;
the President shall submit within 48 hours to the Speaker of the House of Representatives and to the President pro tempore of the Senate a report, in writing, setting forth—
(A)the circumstances necessitating the introduction of United States Armed Forces;
(B)the constitutional and legislative authority under which such introduction took place; and
(C)the estimated scope and duration of the hostilities or involvement.``
Marksman 03/19/2023 09:28 PM
If you want to change when the report is required I don't necessarily see an issue with that. But there would be severe consequences to our national defense if we reduced the period of required withdrawals from 60 days to 7 days.
AG Charlotte Davidson 03/19/2023 09:30 PM
Again, I’m not changing the period of required withdrawals ( have y’all even read the bill). The report is required within 7 days, the timeframe for Congress to act on it remains 60 days.
Marksman 03/19/2023 09:32 PM
Your intention may not be to change the period of required withdrawals. But your implementation means that is exactly what would happen
Marksman 03/19/2023 09:32 PM
If your only intention would be to require a report then Section 3(a) of your bill is sufficient
AG Charlotte Davidson 03/19/2023 09:35 PM
I see, well I’m happy to work with the committee to amend it.
Marksman 03/19/2023 09:36 PM
Even if you don't agree with what I am saying. You don't have to just look at the US code or take my word for it. You can take the word of the Congressional Research Service. In a report published by the CRS in March 2019 they said

> Section 5(b) was intended to provide teeth for the War Powers Resolution. After a report “is
> submitted or is required to be submitted pursuant to section 4(a)(1), whichever is earlier,” **Section
> 5(b) requires the President to terminate the use of U.S. Armed Forces after 60 days **unless
> Congress (1) has declared war or authorized the action; (2) has extended the period by law; or (3)
> is physically unable to meet as a result of an armed attack on the United States. The 60 days can
> be extended for 30 days by the President if he certifies that “unavoidable military necessity
> respecting the safety of United States Armed Forces” requires their continued use in the course of
> bringing about their removal.
Marksman 03/19/2023 09:36 PM
And in your bill you are amending the very same section that requires the termination of use of military force

> Section 5, subsection (b), of Public Law 93-148 shall be amended to say, “Within sixty seven calendar days after a report is submitted or is required to be submitted pursuant to section 4(a)(1), whichever is earlier, the President shall terminate any use of United States Armed Forces with respect to which such report was submitted (or required to be submitted), unless the Congress (1) has declared war or has enacted a specific authorization for such use of United States Armed Forces, (2) has extended by law such sixty-day seven-day period, or (3) is physically unable to meet as a result of an armed attack upon the United States. Such sixty-day seven-day period shall be extended for not more than an additional thirty twenty days if the President determines and certifies to the Congress in writing that unavoidable military necessity respecting the safety of United States Armed Forces requires the continued use of such armed forces in the course of bringing about a prompt removal of such forces.”
AG Charlotte Davidson 03/19/2023 09:36 PM
With that helpful clarification, I understand your point now.
Marksman 03/19/2023 09:37 PM
No problem. And I would be willing to work with you to improve this piece of legislation as well.
AG Charlotte Davidson 03/19/2023 09:38 PM
That would be welcomed. I know that my intentions and beliefs on the legislation is that we need to shorten the gap because it just doesn’t make sense with what happened in the before times when Presidents could achieve two four year terms and the present day with term limits being any President can get two two-month terms.
AG Charlotte Davidson 03/19/2023 09:39 PM
In addition to rebalancing the separation of powers.
Marksman 03/19/2023 09:42 PM
I believe that its important that there is a continual and open dialogue between the Legislative Branches and the Executive Branch on perhaps one of the most important functions of our country which is deciding whether or not to enter into conflict.

However at the same time we must make sure to secure our national defense and that means the ability to concentrate force at precise moments and at precise locations when necessary. Even if the terms of Presidents have shortened, the duration of conflicts and crisis's unfortunately have not correspondingly decreased

Remy Danton 05/06/2023 12:19 PM
<@921950633316216832> I am open to hear what your objections are and if it can be resolved
Rep. Roberto Telles (I-MI-LN) 05/06/2023 12:20 PM
The bill sucks.
Remy Danton 05/06/2023 12:20 PM
How if I may ask?
Rep. Roberto Telles (I-MI-LN) 05/06/2023 12:22 PM
I don’t think we need to change the ethics rules.
Rep. Roberto Telles (I-MI-LN) 05/06/2023 12:23 PM
Attempts to are purely political—we should have no need to change rules that have been governing the court for years.
Remy Danton 05/06/2023 12:24 PM
The thing is that there are NO rules, if you read my findings. Other federal judges have rules of ethics except for the Supreme Court.
Remy Danton 05/06/2023 12:25 PM
Sure the Supreme Court has rules of procedures, but there are none regarding ethics or code of conduct.
Rep. Roberto Telles (I-MI-LN) 05/06/2023 12:25 PM
There are rules as the court is checked by the possibility impeachment in which ethics rules are nothing but excessive guidelines for—at the Supreme Court level-anyways. How do you plan to enforce these rules?
Remy Danton 05/06/2023 12:25 PM
Have you read the bill?
Rep. Roberto Telles (I-MI-LN) 05/06/2023 12:26 PM
There is a reason the Supreme Court doesn’t have ethic rules, it’s not enforceable.
Remy Danton 05/06/2023 12:26 PM
Sure there is possibility of impeachment but I believe that there should be other ways in which Justices can be reprimanded without being removed from office.
Remy Danton 05/06/2023 12:28 PM
That's why my bill grants the Judicial Conference the power to enforce the code of conduct. I didn't make it personal that's why the Bill doesn't establish the code of conduct but leaves it to the Judicial Conference. However the bill tells what should be included in the code alongside other rules.
Rep. Roberto Telles (I-MI-LN) 05/06/2023 12:33 PM
The problem is this is an impermissible way to enforce ethic rules on the Supreme Court—only the Supreme Court can enforce it themselves otherwise it is a separation-of-powers issue.
Remy Danton 05/06/2023 12:35 PM
I understand your concerns about the separation of powers and the autonomy of the Supreme Court. However, the goal of this bill isn't to impose our will on the Court or undermine its authority. Instead, we're trying to create a transparent and consistent ethical framework that applies to all branches of government, including the judiciary. We're not trying to infringe on the Court's independence, but rather provide guidance and improve accountability while maintaining respect for their unique role. Ultimately, our aim is to ensure the public can have confidence in the integrity and impartiality of the Supreme Court, and we believe this bill is a step in that direction while still upholding the Constitution's checks and balances.
❤️ 1

I am considering filing a joint resolution of impeachment for the current President of the United States based on Article II, Section III of the US Constitution. <@489916127863111721> what would be the difference between the FDA and the Food Safety Administration?
Amb. Pluribus (D-LN) 05/16/2024 01:42 AM
FDA is going to become the Federal Drug Administration and deal with all drug related policy issues, including supplements and such, and would remain under Health and Human Services.

Food Safety Administration of course gets food and such, and gets that from FDA's current food inspection operations and Department of Agriculture's food inspection operations, and becomes an independent agency.
